\begin_layout Standard
This investigation used two types of climate data.
 Reanalysis datasets and high-quality climate observations.
 This sub-section briefly explains what reanalysis data are and describes
 the three datasets chosen: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The Twentieth Century Reanalysis Project
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (20CR), the Met Office Hadley Centre’s sea ice and sea surface temperature
 (SST) dataset (HadISST1), and the Australian Climate Observations Reference
 Network (ACORN-SAT).
 The first two are reanalysis datasets while the last comprises weather
 station data.
 The main criteria to select these data was the length of its records.
 The three datasets cover more than 100 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Climate research relies on long-term datasets for understanding climate
 variability and change.
 However, the availability of information often reaches only the range of
 instrumental records.
 Reanalysis projects or “retrospective” analysis are international efforts
 created to address this problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 These projects produce reliable global circulation datasets.
 Several reanalysis projects have been created to date (e.g.
 the 1948–present NCEP–NCAR reanalysis dataset, the 1957–2002 ECMWF reanalysis,
 the 1979–present Japan Meteorological Agency reanalysis).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Twentieth Century Reanalysis Project (20CR) is a reanalysis product
 derived from the assmilation of sub-daily surface pressure reports, monthly
 sea-surface temperature and observed sea-ice data as boundary conditions
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

.
 Version two of the 20CR—available when the project started—yields atmospheric
 fields for the period 1871–2008.
 This project comprises 56 possible realisations of the atmosphere.
 Since in this project it is not feasible to use every realization, the
 study analysed the ensemble mean.
 The dataset yields 6-hourly daily data with a spatial grid of 2x2
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The 20CR data is avaliable at 24 vertical levels.
 Most analyses in this investigation used the 1000 hPa (near surface) values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Met Office Hadley Centre’s sea ice and sea surface temperature (SST)
 dataset (HadISST1) dataset was generated using a reduced space optimal
 interpolation technique to produce high-quality gridded observations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rayner2003"

\end_inset

.
 HadISST1 comprises monthly SST data with a 1x1
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

 resolution.
 These data spans the period 1871-present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These datasets have common intrinsic limitations.
 For example, a limited number of observations in the early decades of the
 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 They present fewer observations in the Southern Hemisphere.
 Additionally, not all variables are equally well represented.
 However, recent results have shown that the 20CR represents well southeastern
 Australia’s climate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ashcroft2014"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the calculation of heatwave events used the Australian
 Climate Observations Reference Network (ACORN-SAT) dataset 
