\begin_layout Subsubsection
Analysis of bushfire acitivity records
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bushfire records are the main data for this research.
 The two databases used have information starting from the early 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 However, their bushfire definitions are different.
 Therefore, it was necessary to investigate area-burnt thresholds in DELWP's
 dataset.
 This process allowed to establish comparisons with Risk Frontier's (RF)
 database.
 Fire events that burnt at least the area set by an arbitrary threshold
 were aggregated.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analyses examined two periods: 1911-1960 and 1961-2011.
 It started from 1911 since meteorological data Victoria is more reliable
 from this year.
 The year 2011 was selected since RF's data was available until this year.
 On the other hand, splitting in half the period of analysis was an important
 decision.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wang2013"

\end_inset

 argue that the response of climate modes variability can change over long
 periods of time.
 Therefore, this chapter aimed to explore the changes in fire activity between
 the first and second half of the 20
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 century.
 The next chapter investigates how these changes are linked to climate modes
 variability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investigation of fire activity focused on the season December-January-Februa
ry (DJF).
 An appraisal of the datasets revealed that most bushfires in Victoria occur
 in DJF.
 For example, 73% of bushfires (31 out of 42 events) in DELWP database occurred
 in this season (1961-2010).
 For RF's database, the percentage increases to 83% (43 out 52 events).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Computation of heatwave dates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nairn2009"

\end_inset

proposed a system to define heatwaves—with further details provided in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nairn2013"

\end_inset

—.
 The defintion was adopted because it combines two useful concepts.
 The first concept is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Excess Heat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 This criterion refers to a high heat period that was not dispersed due
 to elevated temperatures overnight.
 The second concept is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Heat Stress
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It relates to a period that has been warmer in comparison to the previous
 month.
 Using these propositions, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nairn2009"

\end_inset

 created an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Excess Heat Factor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
EHI_{sig}=(T_{i}+T_{i+1}+T_{i+2})/3-T_{95}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
EHI_{accl}=(T_{i}+T_{i+1}+T_{i+2})/3-(T_{i-1}+...+T_{i-30})/30
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
EHF=EHI_{sig}*\left|EHI_{accl}\right|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T:$
\end_inset

 Daily average of maximum and minimum temperature.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T_{95}:$
\end_inset

 95
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 percentile of the long-term daily temperature (maximum and minimum temperature
 average).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $EHI_{sig}:$
\end_inset

 Excess heat sub-index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $EHI_{accl}:$
\end_inset

 Heat stress sub-index.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $EHF:$
\end_inset

Excess heat factor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis used a second heatwave definition.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pezza2012"

\end_inset

 describe the alternative approach used.
 This definition was selected because it represents extreme heatwave events.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pezza2012"

\end_inset

 define a heatwave as a period of at least 3 consecutive days with maximum
 temperature above the 90
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 percentile.
 The criteria also requires that minimum temperature is above the 90
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
th
\end_layout

\end_inset

 percentile in the second and third days.
 The definition uses monthly climatologies.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
